    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, seeking the arcane knowledge of the goblin's tax formula, are we? Very well, brave seeker of wisdom. The formula used to calculate the interest on your student loan for a single month is quite straightforward, though it may seem as mysterious as a goblin's whisper in the night. The interest for a month is calculated by multiplying the remaining principal balance by the monthly interest rate. Here's the formula, stripped of goblin metaphors for clarity:\n\nInterest for the month = Principal balance x Monthly interest rate\n\nThe monthly interest rate is determined by dividing the annual interest rate by 12 (the number of months in a year). So, if your loan has an annual interest rate of 5%, the monthly interest rate would be 5% / 12 = 0.4167%.\n\nLet's say you have a remaining principal balance of $10,000 on your student loan. The interest for the month would be calculated as follows:\n\nInterest for the month = $10,000 x 0.004167 (0.4167% as a decimal) = $41.67\n\nSo, out of your monthly payment, $41.67 would go towards paying the interest for that month. The rest of your payment would",
